{"slug":"brokers","graph":"companies","title":"The brokers","sub":"who sits in the structural holes — and whose intros are real","headline":"The labs aside, the market's widest structural hole belongs to <strong>LangChain (LangGraph / LangSmith) (constraint 0.09, 15 ties across 5 verticals)</strong> — on real business edges alone the seat passes to Microsoft (0.11).","prose":{"intro":"<p>Who in this market can actually broker an introduction? Not the best-connected node — the least <em>constrained</em> one: the company whose contacts don't already know each other, so it sits across the open gaps between clusters. Those gaps are where deal flow, hiring, and early market intelligence move first.</p>","how":"<p>Burt's constraint is a concentration score on your ego network — think Herfindahl index for your attention: it's high when all your ties fold back into one tight clique, low when your contacts are mutual strangers you alone connect. Effective size is the companion statistic: your degree discounted for redundancy, exactly like effective sample size for correlated data — 12 contacts who all know each other count as far fewer than 12 independent ones. We rank the 171-node giant component ascending by constraint, keeping the 132 nodes with degree ≥ 3 (39 lower-degree nodes are trivially constrained and excluded). Then we re-run on business edges only — customer, partner, and platform relationships — because a bridge made of shared-investor edges may never convert to a warm intro; the second table is the honest broker list.</p>","method":"<p>Burt (1992), <em>Structural Holes</em>: constraint c<sub>i</sub> = Σ<sub>j</sub>(p<sub>ij</sub> + Σ<sub>q</sub> p<sub>iq</sub>p<sub>qj</sub>)²; effective size via the Borgatti (1997) simplification for binary graphs; networkx implementations of both. Full mixed run: giant component of the company graph (171 nodes, 474 edges; smaller components excluded — constraint is a local statistic, so this only drops their few eligible members). Business-only run: giant component of the business-edge subgraph (75 nodes, 112 edges, 26 nodes over the degree floor). The funding graph was checked and not shipped: it has zero triangles (a forest), so constraint reduces to exactly 1/degree for all 13 nodes over the floor — the statistic would restate degree and nothing else.</p>"},"caveat":"AoC's own 5 edges are 4 competitor ties plus one unverified, inferred business tie (AIUC), so its mixed-graph seat (constraint 0.20, rank 38 of 132) is rivalry-flavored — and in the business-only graph the AoC–AIUC pair is an isolated dyad off the giant component, so AoC is absent from the warm-intro list entirely. Note also that none of the top 25 mixed-graph brokers are investor-vc nodes: the mapped VCs sit at this graph's periphery, not in its holes.","inputs":{"companies":{"nodes":188,"edges":492}},"data":{"brokers":[{"id":"anthropic","label":"Anthropic","vertical":"frontier lab","degree":45,"constraint":0.047,"effSize":42.2,"spans":6,"flag":null},{"id":"openai","label":"OpenAI","vertical":"frontier lab","degree":30,"constraint":0.066,"effSize":27.3,"spans":6,"flag":null},{"id":"langchain-langgraph-langsmith","label":"LangChain (LangGraph / LangSmith)","vertical":"infra platform","degree":15,"constraint":0.09,"effSize":13.9,"spans":5,"flag":"broker by trade"},{"id":"cognition-devin","label":"Cognition (Devin)","vertical":"agent native startup","degree":16,"constraint":0.102,"effSize":14.1,"spans":7,"flag":null},{"id":"microsoft","label":"Microsoft","vertical":"enterprise other","degree":18,"constraint":0.107,"effSize":15.2,"spans":4,"flag":"broker by trade"},{"id":"glean","label":"Glean","vertical":"agent native startup","degree":12,"constraint":0.111,"effSize":10.5,"spans":6,"flag":null},{"id":"protect-ai-palo-alto-networks","label":"Protect AI (Palo Alto Networks)","vertical":"security eval vendor","degree":16,"constraint":0.112,"effSize":13.8,"spans":3,"flag":null},{"id":"bolt-stackblitz","label":"Bolt (StackBlitz)